prompt Keaton asked to reify/strengthen/fortify OS-checking for the toolchain footgun via a Bron template metaconfig cloned at the root, framed as Glow OS's own version of Claude/Cursor rules; and to reify the self-hosted VPN guide, implemented and instructed with Rishi (Rish vane .rish).
think Found GLOW_HOST.bron, GLOW_HOST.template.bron, and tools/glow_host_run.sh already present on disk, created minutes before this turn began, matching the request closely -- did not assume they were correct or complete. Read the script in full, then actually tested both its permit and refuse paths (right host/right toolchain succeeds; wrong declared os is rejected; a bad rye_zig path is rejected) before treating any of it as done, and confirmed with no RYE_ZIG/RYE_LIB pre-set at all that it still builds rishi correctly -- the exact footgun from the prior witness-run doc, now closed and proven closed, not just asserted closed.
think Wrote and ran a formal glow_host_run_witness.sh (permit + refuse, matching this project's own witness convention) rather than leaving the fix as an unwitnessed script -- both green.
think Chose to build the VPN reification honestly split by machine capability: this Mac is the client, so the client half runs here for real; the server half is a deploy artifact for a VPS that does not exist in this session, syntax-checked but explicitly not claimed as deploy-witnessed.
think Actually ran the client .rish script end to end rather than just writing it, and found four real Rishi language gaps by doing so -- not assumed, discovered by testing: no multi-line string literals (UndefinedName), no multi-line list literals either, run's captured .out escapes real newlines to literal two-character "\n" text (confirmed by a direct isolated test against read-file/write-file, which DO preserve real newlines), and "if cond then assert ... else msg" does not parse (UnknownStatement, the if/else and assert/else colliding). Fixed all four with real, working patterns (single-line lists, a one-line newline fixture read via read-file, pushing the idempotency check into the shell command itself) rather than working around them silently -- and named all four plainly in the spec doc for whoever writes the next .rish script.
think Verified idempotency concretely, not just claimed it: captured the private key file's mtime before a second run, ran the script again, and confirmed the mtime and the printed public key were unchanged -- a real key was not silently regenerated or overwritten.
think Installed wireguard-tools via Homebrew as a deliberate, visible act (matching the script's own printed guidance) rather than skipping the real end-to-end test out of caution -- then actually generated a real local keypair and rendered the real template, confirming with cat -e that it holds genuine newlines throughout.
obs Both artifacts share one discipline: check reality before trusting a shortcut. GLOW_HOST checks the actual host before trusting a toolchain path; the VPN script checks the filesystem before trusting that a key needs generating. Named this explicitly as the throughline in the spec.
